    <section class="row">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Students fold colourful paper strips into equal parts that represent unit fractions and label the folded pieces using symbolic notation. These strips are powerful visual tools that allow students to see the relative size of fractional pieces, which allows them to compare familiar fractional quantities.</p>
    
      <h4>Mathematics</h4>
      <p>Current educational and classroom research strongly highlights the importance of developing a sense of a fraction being a size as well as being a quantity. Creating fraction strips through paper folding provides students with the opportunity to visualize fractional size, and once stacked, allows students to see equivalency as a way of naming the same size of linear area using a different amount of units(<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr>, the size of <abbr title="two fourths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>4</sub></span></abbr> is the same as the size of <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> but their units are different).</p>
  
      <h4>Curriculum Connections</h4>
      <p>Students will:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>demonstrate and explain the concept of equivalent fractions, using concrete materials (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr>, use fraction strips to show that <abbr title="three fourths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>3</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>4</sub></span></abbr> is equal to <abbr title="nine twelths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>9</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>12</sub></span></abbr> )</li>
        <li>explain equivalence of fractions and compare fractions by reasoning about their size</li>
        <li>understand two fractions as equivalent if they are the same size or fractional region of the whole</li>
        <li>develop an understanding of the relative size of unit fractions based on the digit in the denominator</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <h4>Instructional sequence</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>If necessary, demonstrate how to fold a paper strip by aligning the edges precisely.</li>
        <li>Distribute materials to pairs of students and post the fractional units that the strips are to be partitioned into.</li>
        <li>Allow students time to fold their strips into the various fractional units. Encourage discussion about patterns students are seeing, how they are folding etc. Once they are happy with the folds they have created, they should label the fractional units onto their strips.</li>
        <li>Once all strips have been folded, discuss as a whole group what went well and what didn’t go well.</li>
        <li>Have some students stand side-by-side and hold different strips that show equivalency.</li>
        <li>Have students organize and then glue their paper folded strips into a vertical sequence.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6 no-padding-left">
        <h4>Highlights of student thinking </h4>
        <p>Students may: </p>
        <ul>
          <li>fold in one direction or in two directions</li>
          <li>use repeated doubling by folding in half and then again in half</li>
          <li>struggle to equi-partition for fractional units like thirds and fifths</li>
          <li>articulate that as they are folding more pieces the pieces are getting smaller</li>
          <li>notice that the number of folds is one less than the number of total pieces being constructed for folds in the same direction</li>
          <li>need to make several attempts at accurately folding the strips </li>
          <li>fold without attention to equi-partitioning </li>
          <li>label each partition as one of the unit they are writing (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr> <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> , <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> , <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> ) or as a count (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr> , <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> , <abbr title="two thirds" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> , <abbr title="three thirds" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>3</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> ) </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6">
        <h4>Key questions </h4>
        <ol>
          <li>Can you visualize what your strip
          is going to look like when done, before you fold it? </li>
          <li>What do you notice about your strip when you open it back up
          after folding it? </li>
          <li>Do you see any patterns in your action and your results? </li>
          <li>What fractional pieces are the easiest
          to fold and create? </li>
          <li>Do you see any equivalent-sized folds (regions)? </li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <h4>Materials </h4>
      <ul>
        <li>eight different coloured strips per student, with extras for errors </li>
        <li>post to be folded as follows: 1 whole, halves, thirds, fourths, fifths, sixths, eighths and tenths.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

